<Layout>
  <h1>Updated YDS Proposal</h1>

  <p>You can read more about the what and why on the <a href="related.html">related thoughts</a> page, basically it's breaking up exposure and movement technique and adding more modifiers to classes 2-4 similar to what class 5 has. Major structural issues that are under consideration are listed in <a href="https://github.com/erutan/backpacker-yds/issues">this github repo</a>, feel free to comment or add a new one!</p>

  <h2>Classes (movement over terrain)</h2>

  <p>Classes are used to break down the 'types of movement' or 'modes of travel' over terrain (focusing on off-trail / cross country / XC) and the general level of technique required. They are abstractions and do not always directly map to difficulty or how preferable a route is. They are meant to be a basic check on expectations for what is considered "on route".</p>

  <h3>Class 1: Walking</h3>

  <p>This terrain encompasses the following, and falls into what would be within expectations for a maintained trail:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Casual:</strong> walking on wide very even low angle ground. Little to no attention needs to be paid to footing.</li>
    <li><strong>Attentive:</strong> easy terrain can be narrower (step aside to let someone pass) and there are obstacles to avoid though you can generally step on a flat or nearly flat surface. This could also be a moderately high angle slope where traction isn't guaranteed. You have to look down at your feet occasionally, but it's not that much harder than casually walking.</li>
    <li><strong>Surefooted:</strong> you are moving over small stable talus, roots, or other obstacles and have to step on uneven or angled surfaces, but the obstacles aren't large or difficult enough to require the use of hands.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>If going off-trail you are assumed to be capable of moving surefootedly. Routefinding is generally straightforward.</p>

