  <h3>Class 2: Using hands for assistance</h3>

  <p>This is moving over more rough or rugged terrain that is uneven or steep enough that it'd be reasonable to expect people to occasionally use their hands (or trekking poles) to maintain traction (balance, pushing or pulling off obstacles, extra point of contact, but walking/hiking and not moving from hold to hold). It can be broken down into 3 sub-grades:</p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>2-</strong> (or 2 easy): You need to occasionally place a hand on a piece of talus or steep slab to steady yourself. Depending on your direction, conditions, and experience some could do it hands free, but the obstacles are large enough using hands for balance is reasonable.</li>
    <li><strong>2:</strong> The terrain is rugged enough that you are regularly using your hands for balance, or pushing off of them to boost yourself up or down larger obstacles. This can also be steep slab that require tight routefinding to move on safely or a slope with poor traction where trekking poles maintain traction as boots slip.</li>
    <li><strong>2+</strong> (or 2 hard): You are mantling or dropping off of larger obstacles that can't simply walk up, but not quite "climbing". This includes reaching up to the top of a ledge to pull yourself up, holding onto the top and dropping down it, using your hands to hold onto a steep slope while mostly walking up it, clambering on and off large deadfall, etc. You might be a couple feet off the ground but quickly standing up again.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Technique, experience, pack weight, weather, direction, height, fitness, and other factors can impact subjective perception - it doesn't mean you're off-route if something is rated 2 but it feels 2+, but you shouldn't be actually climbing from hold to hold suspended off of the ground for more than a move or two.</p>

  <p>Routefinding can become quite complex, as portions of the route are often obscured.</p>

