  <h3>Class 3: Simple Climbing</h3>

  <p>You are using both hands to hang and hold onto rock (or roots) and climb, while the holds are large and easy to locate, your feet need to find footholds to continue ascending as your hands move to new handholds. Simple climbing is intuitive and kind of "jungle gymish". Your feet will be off the ground and supporting your weight as you climb. Climbing/approach oriented footwear helps, but anything you can hike well in should handle class 3 ok.</p>

  <p>Adding in the fall risk modifiers further down will help clarify what "Class 3" means for a route - a lot of people would be comfortable on 3 PG but not 3 X.</p>

  <p>Secor's favorite description was given by Steve Roper: "Imagine climbing a steep, narrow staircase outside of a tall building without benefit of a railing: scary but easy."</p>

  <ul class="accordion" data-accordion data-allow-all-closed="true">
    <li class="accordion-item" data-accordion-item>
      <a href="#" class="accordion-title">Safety Note</a>
      <div class="accordion-content" data-tab-content>
        <p>It's "simple" climbing, but carrying a fully loaded pack up Class 3 can be VERY different from doing it unladen. The extra weight makes vertical moves more difficult - more critically your center of balance may be further away from the rock pulling you away from it and pack itself can become a physical obstacle if going up a crack or relatively tight space. If using trekking poles, they'd generally be tucked away. It's not fun having one get stuck in a 15 foot crack halfway up it and having to downclimb and try and work it out while hanging onto rock.</p>
        <p>If you aren't experienced carrying a loaded pack up Class 3, it can help to travel with someone more experienced who can shuttle your pack up, explain and demonstrate the route, and if necessary wait at the top to grasp your wrist or stay at the bottom to spot you and or push your feet onto holds and call out moves. Trip leaders - it's on you to make sure novices make it safely up Class 3 with minimal risk and psychological damage.</p>
        <p>There is no limit to the height of such terrain, and exposure risk can be involved especially if bagging a peak or traversing a narrow ridge. If novices are along it can be a good idea to be prepared to provide a rope and requisite gear to belay them if they feel uncomfortable.</p>
