  <h3>Class 4: Climbing (rope recommended)</h3>

  <p>A noticeable step up from class 3 in terms of technique required. Class 4 is vertical or very close to it, with smaller holds and is often exposed (though it can also be a short but more technical section that would fall under the PG modifier below). It can be a little tricky to figure out and require some proper rock climbing techniques, but it's still relatively straightforward. Class 4 generally should not be done with a full pack. Having at least approach shoes or "high route boots" is highly recommended - footwear with roomy floppy toe boxes are comfortable on trail but are likely to slip off smaller holds. Rope is advised to be be in use though experienced individuals will often go without at their own risk.</p>

  <p>Expect overlap in the lower difficulties of Class 5 (up to around 5.5) inside what's considered Class 4. If that seems dumb and you're interested in geeking out on technical details, this is <a href="https://www.summitpost.org/class-four-is-a-myth-problems-in-yds/891794">an epic rant on Class 4</a>. Class 4 is kind of a mess, but it's still a useful tool for describing moving over terrain. You can think of it as Class 3+ <em>or</em> 5-.</p>

